AB  - People's inherent ability tends to deteriorate as they get older, and their health problems get more complicated and chronic. As people get older, multimorbidity—the simultaneous occurrence of many chronic conditions becomes more common. Health systems around the world struggle to adapt to the great range of physical and mental abilities of older people and to encourage good trajectories of healthy aging from an early age. The abilities of an older person can change quickly—in some circumstances, over the course of hours. Care systems struggle to adapt rapidly enough to meet a person's changing demands. As a result of the impending lack of healthcare workers qualified to provide for senior citizens, adopting elder-friendly technologies may level the playing field in the industry. A decision support system can send alerts to elderly people, their family members, and carers, recommending the necessary interventions to halt further health deterioration, based on the statistically significant changes that can be found in daily records using a combination of modern data mining techniques. This study examines the most recent Internet of Things (IoT) technology can assist carers in improving the health, safety, and quality of life of independent elderly persons. The system is based on the behavior of senior citizens at home.
