AB  - The Internet of Things (IoT) and software applications have radically improved healthcare, especially in terms of detecting and reporting adverse events that compromise patient safety. With the prompt detection and reporting of adverse occurrences, this literature review seeks to give a thorough understanding of the origin, applications, benefits, and challenges of IoT and software solutions in improving patient safety. A thorough literature search was undertaken in six scholarly databases including, PubMed, IEEE Xplore, ScienceDirect, Scopus, and Google Scholar, to identify articles related to IoT and software applications for detecting and reporting patient safety adverse events (AEs). Seventy-four pertinent publications were found and included after a thorough search of the peer-reviewed literature. To gain an understanding of the design components, the history of IoT applications, and the wide range of application domains in patient safety adverse event detection and reporting, these publications underwent critical analysis. The review identified a promising path for timely and precise adverse event identification through the combined efforts of IoT technology, including wearables, sensors, and real-time monitoring systems, with sophisticated software applications for the administration of medications, detection, and prevention of falls, and remote patient monitoring, all of which improved patient safety. Despite the promising prospects of IoT technologies, problems with data privacy, security, and scalability were identified as challenges to their successful integration into health systems' safety. The critical importance of IoT and software technologies in modernizing patient safety adverse event detection and reporting is highlighted by this study. This calls for improved knowledge in integrating IoT technological solutions into safe healthcare practices through collaborative research, and interventional studies to assess the impact it has on health outcomes of hospitalized patients.
